A man sits beside Father Time at the edge of the universe.

"Why do you come here?" He asks.

<span style="font-family:Grenze Gotisch">"It is the only place where I am insignificant. My concept here is non-existent, my role meaningless. I am not feared as a soul stealer, but rather greeted with cold indifference."</span>

"What's it like? To have nothing but time?"

<span style="font-family:Grenze Gotisch">"Ironically, I will fade with time. When the last living organism fades to dust, when brown dwarfs cool down, when black holes are reduced to nothing. I will return to darkness. And when the universe restarts with a bang, when the first star forms, I will be reborn. Ever observing. Ever watching."</span>

Father Time turns towards the man.

<span style="font-family:Grenze Gotisch">"Do you need time?"</span>

"Ideally I'd want years," the man admits, "but I know you can't do that. Can I just have an hour? Please?" 

<span style="font-family:Grenze Gotisch">"It is granted."</span>

The man returns. He takes in the familiar sight of his surroundings, then he waits. Waits for one person. One very special person. He fears his hour will be up before his arrival, that he will never see him again. But in the last 57 seconds of his time which remained, he came. The man, so used to repressing his feelings, let it all out.

