There once was a man from Nantucket

Um, how did the rest go again? 

Who was this guy, anyway?

Is he me?

Is he you?

I've forgotten it all.

...I walk out of the abandoned mall. I turn around, and it is gone. Not a single brick in sight. I wipe the sweat off of my brow, and freeze. My fingers brush against a thin, almost invisible groove running down my forehead. When did that get there? No matter, I walk on. My legs hurt. My lungs hurt. My head hurts. Everything hurts. But then, I reach a clearing in the forest. In the middle of it sits a log cabin, thick black smoke drifting out the chimney. Inside, an empty fireplace holds blackened soot and an armchair sits stoically nearby. Beside the armchair is a nightstand, and on the nightstand is a cassette player. On that cassette player are the words, hastily written in fading black marker, "Forget it". But I don't want to. I want to remember.

And so I play the tape.
