I leave the log cabin. craning my head towards the sky, I watch as clouds overhead blot out the moon, descending this place into darkness. The air seems to freeze, and tiny white dots drift down from the sky. It's... snowing. Snowing like when I lost him. When I was sent here. My head hurts. It hurts so much. I touch my cheek, and my hand pulls away sticky and covered in a liquid I can't discern in the darkness. I walk. And walk. And walk. And walk. I walk for a long time. Step,
<br>ㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤby step,
<br>ㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤㅤby step.
<br><center>Where are you, dad?</center>


I make it to another clearing. This time, a lake sits in the middle, its dark surface rippling as the currents run through it. Beyond the lake is a single tree, unbothered by the now heavy snowfall. No snow seems to settle on its leaves as though it has some protective ward around it. Curious. I approach the edge of the lake, staring at the shimmering surface. I extend a leg...
<br> And the water underfoot freezes over. Emboldened, I take another step, then another, then another. The lake freezes over, as if inviting me to cross over, wanting me to reach that tree over yonder. The tree grows <big>larger and</big><big><big> larger</big></big> as I approach steadily. As I step onto the soil once more, I approach the invisible boundary separating the snow and the tree. I take a tentative step in, and the air around me instantly feels leagues warmer. The tree carries a sort of confidence in itself, proud of standing tall for generations. I part my lips.

"...How do you live so long?"

The tree does not answer, most likely keeping its secrets from me.

"Do you fear being forgotten? For nothing to know how tall you stood for so long? The winters, the droughts you endured?"

<span style="font-family:Medieval Sharp">"No, I do not."</span>

"But why? Why don't you fear? Don't you want to be remembered?"

<span style="font-family:Medieval Sharp">"I would rather fade away, than for strangers to utter my name when they do not know what it means."</span>

"...What's your name?"

<span style="font-family:Medieval Sharp">"I have no name. But if I did, I would like to be called Regis."</span>

I sit in silence for a long time, looking up at the thicket of leaves.

"...What was your time?"

<span style="font-family:Medieval Sharp">"Long ago. I stay purely out of stubbornness."</span>

"If you let go, I will too."

<span style="font-family:Medieval Sharp">"..."</span>

<span style="font-family:Medieval Sharp">"Farewell."</span>

In the blink of an eye, the tree which stood so tall, so proud, vanished. Though, the warmth does not leave. It stays. It stays for a long time. I continue walking, past where the tree once stood and into the surrounding, less impressive, forest. The trees seem to stare at me, judging my flaws openly. They mock, ridicule and threaten me. But I walk. And walk. And walk. 

